title: No Artists, Only Alarms: Beijing’s “Exhibit”

author: China Insights
description:
The CCP’s Fourth Plenum has opened, but the entire Chinese news system has gone “mute”: zero footage, zero official dispatches, zero content. Xinhua ran a lone editorial, “Xinwen Lianbo” downplayed it, and the outside world is wondering—is it that the outcome isn’t settled, factional infighting is stuck, or the pace is being deliberately controlled? From the official media’s silence to tremors in the military, this “meeting without images” has pulled back the curtain on Zhongnanhai’s eeriest quiet.

Trump’s 155% tariff countdown is underway. The United States and Australia are joining forces with a $2.2 billion plan to build a rare-earths alliance, squeezing the CCP’s lifeline! The rare-earths gambit has backfired, exports are being choked off, nine PLA full generals have fallen, and after twelve years of anti-corruption the more they fight, the more corrupt it becomes—Xi Jinping is trapped in a dead end of total loss of control. title: China in Crisis: Xi Cornered

author: China Insights
description:
Beijing’s political skies are turbulent! On the eve of the CCP’s Fourth Plenum, unprecedented “elders returning to court” broke out: Hu Jintao, Wen Jiabao, Li Ruihuan, and Wang Yang all appeared, while Zhu Rongji, bedridden, signed in support of institutional reform. Multiple leaks claim Xi Jinping unusually reviewed his economic mistakes at the meeting and even said he was “willing to yield,” while the military’s Zhang Youxia reportedly declared, “The army obeys the collective, not the individual!” Even more startling, two Politburo Standing Committee slates—Plan A and Plan B—are said to be circulating in Beijing’s political circles, pointing to an end to one-man rule and a return to collective leadership. The authorities have not confirmed any of this, but the political world is already boiling—this Fourth Plenum may be the tipping point for a reboot of the CCP system.
